<div>

<img class="macmini" src="https://ipowerresale.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/mac-mininosd.png">

<h2 class="macminititle">MacBook Pro</h2>

<p class="macminiparagraph">I have been on the lookout for a used Mini / Micro PC with a i5 / i7, to be configured as a Home Centre PC. (File server, print server, media center etc.)
My idea was to configure everything and hide away the PC on top of book shelf, connected to a LED TV and wireless keyboard + mouse. It would be always on.
I looked at HP Elitedesk / Prodesk, Lenovo Thinkcenter Tiny, Dell Optiplex Mini and the Mac Mini - all of which are available in the ‘1 liter - 2 liter’ size range.
Recently, I came across a used 2014 model Mac Mini. It was in great condition, a little more than a year old (Bought in Dec 2016) and being sold at around 30% of the current list price. (The 2014 model is still on sale from Apple as of Dec 2017)
Only problem was that it was relatively ‘low spec’, with a i5 (ok), 4GB RAM (I wanted at least 8GB) and a 1TB HDD (I wanted a SSD).
I did quite a lot of research on the feasibility of buying this machine and upgrading it myself - i.e. adding more RAM and a SSD.
But alas, while the HP / Dell / Lenovo machines are designed to make upgrades or DIY easy (Tool-less design), the Mac Mini is purpose designed to make it absolutely anti-DIY.
RAM is soldered to the mother board, removing the SSD requires specialised tools and an elaborate process with the risk of damaging something. In fact the iFixit website lists around 32 different steps (some with specialised tools) to replace the HDD in a Mini.
Bottom line : the 2014 Mac Mini comes with built-in obsolescence. Once you buy, it becomes obsolete pretty soon, with no / un-friendly upgrade options.
In fact the older 2012 Mac Mini are more practical since it is easier to plug in more RAM into them.
Considering the price point, the features, the fact that you need to buy all essential accessories (keyboard, mouse, monitor) additionally to make the Mac Mini into a usable PC, it is easier to just buy Macbook and connect it to an external monitor if you need a big monitor.
Also, if you manage to break something while DIYing your machine, a HP/Dell/Lenovo is cheaper to fix than the Mac Mini.</p>

<a href="https://www.quora.com/Is-it-worth-buying-a-Mac-mini" target="_blank"><strong>Quora</strong></a>

