<h2 class="macprotitle">Mac Pro</h2>

<p class="macproparagraph">Executive summary: If you're not sure if the new Mac Pro is worth buying, then then answer for you is almost certainly no, it's not worth it.
The vast majority of Mac users would be better served with an iMac or MacBook Pro.
It does make sense for a small minority of users; whether or not that includes you depends on your intended use. 
In theory it can be much faster than a top-of-the-line iMac, but having lots of cores only really helps if you can take advantage of them.
Some (but not most) Mac software is multi-threaded, and designed to spread it's work across multiple CPU cores.
Apple's Xcode development tools are probably the best example of a well-designed multithreaded app, in that it's speed scales directly with the number of cores. (Builds happen twice as fast with 12 cores as compared to 6, for example.)
Apple's pro apps, like Final Cut Pro and Logic Pro are also great at taking advantage of multicore processors.
Other Apple apps (Mail, Safari) are multi-threaded, but they aren't CPU intensive, so there's not much benefit there.
But even if your software is mostly designed to run on only a single core, you can still benefit from a multicore Mac if you run multiple apps, because OS X will assign different cores to different apps. Still, even this benefit only makes a difference if you start some major task in one app, and that task will keep running while you switch to a different app.
I happen to have 10 apps open right now, but 9 of them are doing nothing. For my use, it would be a waste of money.</p>

<a href="https://www.quora.com/What-is-Apples-Mac-Pro" target="_blank"><strong>Quora</strong></a>

