<h2 class="macbookairtitle" >MacBook Air</h2>    
    
<p class="macbookairparagraph" >The MBA vs an alternative is really a question of preference, not of superiority. You can go back and forth, Yoga 3 vs MBA (yes, I'm picking on the Yoga 3) and there are wins on both sides of the fence. I mean, can you use your Macbook Air as a touch screen tablet? No, you can't. Oh, but wait, a fully loaded Macbook air is cheaper than a Yoga 3 Pro... and round and round we go. 
I like the Yoga 3. It runs full up windows and that makes it play nice in my cozy little windows network and windows centric world. I like touch screens. If I was in the market for an ultra portable, I'd buy a Yoga 3 Pro before I'd buy a Mac Book Air. I use software that actually doesn't allow you to scale windows below 800 pixels tall and the MBA's low resolution is a genuine deal breaker for that software. 
Does that mean you should rush out to buy a Yoga 3 Pro instead of a MacBook Air? 
No, it doesn't. Many of the advantages of the Yoga 3 may be frittered away by the next generation of Macbook Air, and honestly, if you like Macs then you should buy a Mac! They're good products if they fit your specific needs. If you like it, buy one. If you don't, there are alternatives available that offer different advantages with different trade offs. I have owned several computers in the past, including some laptops (all PCs). I bought a MacBook air, 2008 version, and this was my first Mac computer. 
This was a used, 4 year old laptop that I wanted just to try  Xcode, even knowing it would be kind of slow. 
From a product form point of view, I consider any MacBook Air version the best laptop available, and one should only choose another if a) doesn't have enough budget,  b) needs more horsepower. 
In 2012 - I think the current MBA version was mid 2011 - I was so impressed with the old 2008 MBA, that I decided to get rid of every computer in the house to buy a new 13 inch MBA and a thunderbolt monitor. 
Best decision ever. It wasn't perfect performance wise though. I use Lightroom, Photoshop and some other stuff that would lag, including virtualizing Windows 7 with parallels. It wasn't that it didn't cope, it just felt lagging from time to time, when pushing it. </p>    
    
<a href="https://www.quora.com/Is-Apples-MacBook-Air-worth-buying" target="_blank"><strong>Quora<strong></a>    
    
